#HelloWorld.

‚ÄúMy work is simply to be enjoyed. I considered it escapism, something to indulge in and forget about the bullsh*t.‚Äù Alec West‚Äôs (@alec.fbx) colorful lo-fi renderings throw back to gaming‚Äôs early years. ‚ÄúI make animations that mainly just capture a moment in an ever-growing world, each video being another piece in the puzzle. All my life I have been creating art. In middle school, I would go on websites and watch pivot stick fighter animations all day. I would attempt my own crude versions at home downloading pre-made assets.‚Äù

Alec developed his pixelated world and original character Tri-Tails using free open-source software. ‚ÄúThe work that took a team of 40-plus people 20 years ago, I can do in my room alone today. I am excited to see where these tools will take us and what will be made. I am in a server with extremely talented artists, ranging across many different forms of digital art and software. I don‚Äôt know what I would do without this community. Having people to reach out to for help and just general questions is something I won‚Äôt ever take for granted. This is something anyone should be able to do if they want. It‚Äôs our goal to not only inspire but help them achieve that goal.‚Äù

Video by @alec.fbx
Music by @goreshit.sucks

‚ÄúI like to bottle up auras only I can see, in the hopes other people can see them too,‚Äù says Nat ƒÜmiel, the visual artist and musician who is manifesting the otherworldly, ethereal enigma that is yeule (@yeule).

‚ÄúThe yeule project is a sonic and visual time capsule that snapshots eras of my shape-shifting self and the experience of pathos. Musically, yeule lies somewhere between electronic nu-pop cy-earth music II and indie confessional emo.‚Äù Born in Singapore and based in London, the self-styled ‚Äúglitch princess‚Äù was a quiet and introverted child before finding their sense of belonging online ‚Äî drawing inspiration for yeule from the cyber dimension. ‚ÄúAs a Singaporean artist, I feel proud of representing Southeast Asia in the electronic music scene. I stand for mental health awareness, trans rights and dedicate my work on this earth to the friends I lost, who couldn‚Äôt be seen the way they wanted to be.

I want to hit that spot where it hurts so bad and burns so hot, but you can never take a picture or show anyone what it looked like. Songwriting starts from the dreams and memories that scar the most and end up in my journal in crumpled pieces of paper. I hope it sounds pretty, even though the contents are decaying inside. I won‚Äôt sing something I don‚Äôt mean, and I don‚Äôt play something I don‚Äôt really like. There must be a reason why I chip at this concrete so meticulously, right? To make it look as close as it can to what I have seen with my own eyes.‚Äù

Video by @yeule

Artist Jon Batiste (@jonbatiste) is a whole vibe. üé∂ He‚Äôs heading to the Grammy Awards (@recordingacademy) with 11 different nominations ‚Äî the most of any nominee this year. ü§Øüëè

But before Jon‚Äôs performance at the awards, he met up with friends in New York City for one of his self-proclaimed ‚Äúlove riots.‚Äù

‚ÄúLove riots are like chaotic, fun, impromptu musical parades. It started as something I would do in transit from one place to the next, whether on the way to the recording studio or to rehearsal or even just to the market,‚Äù says Jon. ‚ÄúIt borrows from the second-line tradition of my hometown New Orleans, typically starting with a few people and gathering folks along the way. I love the feeling of ceremony and sense of community that it brings.‚Äù

Meet Jon‚Äôs community and hear his soulful sound from the subway to the studio before tonight‚Äôs show in Las Vegas.
